"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-summer-mcintosh-first-gold-medal-swimming-paris\", \"text\": \"Check out Sports Illustrated\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Daily Rings, our daily Olympics podcast from Mitch Goldich and Dan Gartland. Subscribe wherever you get your podcasts (Apple,Spotify) and find clips onSI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s YouTube page.  NANTERRE, France \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 Summer McIntosh is not yet 18, but when she arrived at the Paris La D\\u00c3\\u00a9fense Arena pool for the 400-meter individual medley final Monday evening, she was not just expected to win a gold medal. It wasassumedshe would win the gold medal. McIntosh had already won silver in the 400 free, and while every Olympic silver is an amazing achievement, silver in a race when Katie Ledecky wins bronze feels even more impressive. But McIntosh merely competes in the 400 free. The 400 IM, she owns.  This is where we would normally talk about the extraordinary pressure a 17-year-old in that situation must feel, but it would be a bit disingenuous. At last year\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s world championships, McIntosh won the 400 IM by more than four seconds.Since then, she has gotten faster: She set the world record of 4:24.38 at the Canadian Olympic Trials.  Pressure was not going to cost McIntosh gold. A stomach virus, maybe. But not pressure.  McIntosh knew it, too, not because she is arrogant, but because she knows what she is capable of.  She said afterward that as she made the turn in the breaststroke, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI kind of looked around to make sure I was in a comfortable lead.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d The race was not even half over.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI definitely knew that I had the gold medal going into that last 100 meters,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d McIntosh said.  It was her first gold medal, and even that sounds absurd, inasmuch as it implies she will win more. But \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 shewillwin more. McIntosh won the 200 butterfly at the last two world championships; that race is Wednesday.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cObviously, I am super happy with the result, but now I am all about the [200] fly on Day Five,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d McIntosh said.  The question, with an athlete who is this good this young, is whether she appreciates how special it is to win gold. McIntosh\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s official answer: \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cOh, yeah, for sure. I mean, definitely pretty surreal. I was very happy to get the job done tonight. That was a goal of mine, to be able to stand on top of the podium and get the gold medal.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  The honest answer is that she probably can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t appreciate this. Not fully. She can understand it intellectually, and she can try to savor it. But McIntosh is still just 17. Appreciation can only come later, after life experience and some tougher moments in the pool allow her to put this into proper emotional context. It is fair to say Michael Phelps appreciates thesix gold medals he won in Athensa lot more now than he did in 2004. Katie Ledecky was 15 when she won her first gold medal. Who can make sense of something like that at 15?  Full appreciation is the gift that McIntosh unknowingly wrapped for herself Monday night, to be opened at a much later date. For now, she at least seems to have avoided the traps that can come with others\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 assumption of greatness.  Somebody asked if she felt any relief at winning gold. It was a reasonable question, considering her dominance. Butreliefat winning gold at 17 years old?  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAbsolutely not,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d McIntosh said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThere is definitely a lot of anticipation going into a race, but I would not say necessarily nerves, and there is no relief. I am just trying to soak up every single moment. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 I still feel like I am my 10-year-old self, and I am just trying to solidify all those dreams I had growing up as a kid. I plan on being in the sport for as long as I can do it.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Michael Rosenberg is a senior writer for Sports Illustrated, covering any and all sports. He writes columns, profiles and investigative stories and has covered almost every major sporting event. He joined SI in 2012 after working at the Detroit Free Press for 13 years, eight of them as a columnist. Rosenberg is the author of \\\"War As They Knew It: Woody Hayes, Bo Schembechler and America in a Time of Unrest.\\\" Several of his stories also have been published in collections of the year's best sportswriting. He is married with three children.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"